     1	---
     2	title: How to upgrade to version 16
     3	nav_title: Version 16
     4	description: Upgrade your Next.js Application from Version 15 to 16.
     5	---
     6	
     7	{/* The content of this doc is shared between the app and pages router. You can use the `<PagesOnly>Content</PagesOnly>` component to add content that is specific to the Pages Router. Any shared content should not be wrapped in a component. */}
     8	
     9	## Upgrading from 15 to 16
    10	
    11	### Using AI Agents with Next.js DevTools MCP
    12	
    13	If you're using an AI coding assistant that supports the [Model Context Protocol (MCP)](https://modelcontextprotocol.io), you can use the **Next.js DevTools MCP** to automate the upgrade process and migration tasks.
    14	
    15	#### Setup
    16	
    17	Add the following configuration to your MCP client, for each coding agent you can read [this section](https://github.com/vercel/next-devtools-mcp#mcp-client-configuration) for configuration details.
    18	
    19	**example:**
    20	
    21	```json filename=".mcp.json"
    22	{
    23	  "mcpServers": {
    24	    "next-devtools": {
    25	      "command": "npx",
    26	      "args": ["-y", "next-devtools-mcp@latest"]
    27	    }
    28	  }
    29	}
    30	```
    31	
    32	For more information, visit the [`next-devtools-mcp`](https://github.com/vercel/next-devtools-mcp) documentation to configure with your MCP client.
    33	
    34	> **Note:** Using `next-devtools-mcp@latest` ensures that your MCP client will always use the latest version of the Next.js DevTools MCP server.
    35	
    36	#### Example Prompts
    37	
    38	Once configured, you can use natural language prompts to upgrade your Next.js app:
    39	
    40	**To upgrade to Next.js 16:**
    41	
    42	Connect to your coding agent and then prompt:
    43	
    44	```txt
    45	Next Devtools, help me upgrade my Next.js app to version 16
    46	```
    47	
    48	**To migrate to Cache Components (after upgrading to v16):**
    49	
    50	Connect to your coding agent and then prompt:
    51	
    52	```txt
    53	Next Devtools, migrate my Next.js app to cache components
    54	```
    55	
    56	Learn more in the documentation [here](/docs/app/guides/mcp).
    57	
    58	### Using the Codemod
    59	
    60	To update to Next.js version 16, you can use the `upgrade` [codemod](/docs/app/guides/upgrading/codemods#160):
    61	
    62	```bash package="pnpm"
    63	pnpm dlx @next/codemod@canary upgrade latest
    64	```
    65	
    66	```bash package="npm"
    67	npx @next/codemod@canary upgrade latest
    68	```
    69	
    70	```bash package="yarn"
    71	yarn dlx @next/codemod@canary upgrade latest
    72	```
    73	
    74	```bash package="bun"
    75	bunx @next/codemod@canary upgrade latest
    76	```
    77	
    78	The [codemod](/docs/app/guides/upgrading/codemods#160) is able to:
    79	
    80	- Update `next.config.js` to use the new `turbopack` configuration
    81	- Migrate from `next lint` to the ESLint CLI
    82	- Migrate from deprecated `middleware` convention to `proxy`
    83	- Remove `unstable_` prefix from stabilized APIs
    84	- Remove `experimental_ppr` Route Segment Config from pages and layouts
    85	
    86	If you prefer to do it manually, install the latest Next.js and React versions:
    87	
    88	```bash package="pnpm"
    89	pnpm add next@latest react@latest react-dom@latest
    90	```
    91	
    92	```bash package="npm"
    93	npm install next@latest react@latest react-dom@latest
    94	```
    95	
    96	```bash package="yarn"
    97	yarn add next@latest react@latest react-dom@latest
    98	```
    99	
   100	```bash package="bun"
   101	bun add next@latest react@latest react-dom@latest
   102	```
   103	
   104	If you are using TypeScript, ensure you also upgrade `@types/react` and `@types/react-dom` to their latest versions.
   105	
   106	## Node.js runtime and browser support
   107	
   108	| Requirement   | Change / Details                                                   |
   109	| ------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------ |
   110	| Node.js 20.9+ | Minimum version now `20.9.0` (LTS); Node.js 18 no longer supported |
   111	| TypeScript 5+ | Minimum version now `5.1.0`                                        |
   112	| Browsers      | Chrome 111+, Edge 111+, Firefox 111+, Safari 16.4+                 |
   113	
   114	## Turbopack by default
   115	
   116	Starting with **Next.js 16**, Turbopack is stable and used by default with `next dev` and `next build`
   117	
   118	Previously you had to enable Turbopack using `--turbopack`, or `--turbo`.
   119	
   120	```json filename="package.json"
   121	{
   122	  "scripts": {
   123	    "dev": "next dev --turbopack",
   124	    "build": "next build --turbopack",
   125	    "start": "next start"
   126	  }
   127	}
   128	```
   129	
   130	This is no longer necessary. You can update your `package.json` scripts:
   131	
   132	```json filename="package.json"
   133	{
   134	  "scripts": {
   135	    "dev": "next dev",
   136	    "build": "next build",
   137	    "start": "next start"
   138	  }
   139	}
   140	```
   141	
   142	If your project has a [custom `webpack`](/docs/app/api-reference/config/next-config-js/webpack) configuration and you run `next build` (which now uses Turbopack by default), the build will **fail** to prevent misconfiguration issues.
   143	
   144	You have a few different ways to address this:
   145	
   146	- **Use Turbopack anyway:** Run with `next build --turbopack` to build using Turbopack and ignore your `webpack` config.
   147	- **Switch to Turbopack fully:** Migrate your `webpack` config to Turbopack-compatible options.
   148	- **Keep using Webpack:** Use the `--webpack` flag to opt out of Turbopack and build with Webpack.
   149	
   150	> **Good to know**: If you see failing builds because a `webpack` configuration was found, but you don't define one yourself, it is likely that a plugin is adding a `webpack` option
   151	
   152	### Opting out of Turbopack
   153	
   154	If you need to continue using Webpack, you can opt out with the `--webpack` flag. For example, to use Turbopack in development but Webpack for production builds:
   155	
   156	```json filename="package.json"
   157	{
   158	  "scripts": {
   159	    "dev": "next dev",
   160	    "build": "next build --webpack",
   161	    "start": "next start"
   162	  }
   163	}
   164	```
   165	
   166	We recommend using Turbopack for development and production. Submit a comment to this [thread](https://github.com/vercel/next.js/discussions/77721), if you are unable to switch to Turbopack.
   167	
   168	### Turbopack configuration location
   169	
   170	The `experimental.turbopack` configuration is out of experimental.
   171	
   172	```ts filename="next.config.ts"
   173	import type { NextConfig } from 'next'
   174	
   175	// Next.js 15 - experimental.turbopack
   176	const nextConfig: NextConfig = {
   177	  experimental: {
   178	    turbopack: {
   179	      // options
   180	    },
   181	  },
   182	}
   183	
   184	export default nextConfig
   185	```
   186	
   187	You can use it as a top-level `turbopack` option:
   188	
   189	```ts filename="next.config.ts"
   190	import type { NextConfig } from 'next'
   191	
   192	// Next.js 16 - turbopack at the top level of nextConfig
   193	const nextConfig: NextConfig = {
   194	  turbopack: {
   195	    // options
   196	  },
   197	}
   198	
   199	export default nextConfig
   200	```
   201	
   202	Make sure to review the `Turbopack` configuration [options](/docs/app/api-reference/config/next-config-js/turbopack). **Next.js 16** introduces various improvements and new options, for example:
   203	
   204	- [Advanced Webpack loader conditions](/docs/app/api-reference/config/next-config-js/turbopack#advanced-webpack-loader-conditions)
   205	- [debugIds](/docs/app/api-reference/config/next-config-js/turbopack#debug-ids)
   206	
   207	### Resolve alias fallback
   208	
   209	In some projects, client-side code may import files containing Node.js native modules. This will cause `Module not found: Can't resolve 'fs'` type of errors.
   210	
   211	When this happens, you should refactor your code so that your client-side bundles do not reference these Node.js native modules.
   212	
   213	However, in some cases, this might not be possible. In Webpack the `resolve.fallback` option was typically used to **silence** the error. Turbopack offers a similar option, using `turbopack.resolveAlias`. In this case, tell Turbopack to load an empty module when `fs` is requested for the browser.
   214	
   215	```ts filename="next.config.ts"
   216	import type { NextConfig } from 'next'
   217	
   218	const nextConfig: NextConfig = {
   219	  turbopack: {
   220	    resolveAlias: {
   221	      fs: {
   222	        browser: './empty.ts', // We recommend to fix code imports before using this method
   223	      },
   224	    },
   225	  },
   226	}
   227	
   228	export default nextConfig
   229	```
   230	
   231	It is preferable to refactor your modules so that client code doesn't ever import from modules using Node.js native modules.
   232	
   233	### Sass node_modules imports
   234	
   235	Turbopack fully supports importing Sass files from `node_modules`. Note that while Webpack allowed the legacy tilde (`~`) prefix, Turbopack does not support this syntax.
   236	
   237	In Webpack:
   238	
   239	```scss filename="styles/globals.scss"
   240	@import '~bootstrap/dist/css/bootstrap.min.css';
   241	```
   242	
   243	In Turbopack:
   244	
   245	```scss filename="styles/globals.scss"
   246	@import 'bootstrap/dist/css/bootstrap.min.css';
   247	```
   248	
   249	If changing the imports is not possible, you can use `turbopack.resolveAlias`. For example:
   250	
   251	```ts filename="next.config.ts"
   252	import type { NextConfig } from 'next'
   253	
   254	const nextConfig: NextConfig = {
   255	  turbopack: {
   256	    resolveAlias: {
   257	      '~*': '*',
   258	    },
   259	  },
   260	}
     1	---
     2	title: How to optimize your Next.js application for production
     3	nav_title: Production
     4	description: Recommendations to ensure the best performance and user experience before taking your Next.js application to production.
     5	---
     6	
     7	Before taking your Next.js application to production, there are some optimizations and patterns you should consider implementing for the best user experience, performance, and security.
     8	
     9	This page provides best practices that you can use as a reference when [building your application](#during-development) and [before going to production](#before-going-to-production), as well as the [automatic Next.js optimizations](#automatic-optimizations) you should be aware of.
    10	
    11	## Automatic optimizations
    12	
    13	These Next.js optimizations are enabled by default and require no configuration:
    14	
    15	<AppOnly>
    16	
    17	- **[Server Components](/docs/app/getting-started/server-and-client-components):** Next.js uses Server Components by default. Server Components run on the server, and don't require JavaScript to render on the client. As such, they have no impact on the size of your client-side JavaScript bundles. You can then use [Client Components](/docs/app/getting-started/server-and-client-components) as needed for interactivity.
    18	- **[Code-splitting](/docs/app/getting-started/linking-and-navigating#how-navigation-works):** Server Components enable automatic code-splitting by route segments. You may also consider [lazy loading](/docs/app/guides/lazy-loading) Client Components and third-party libraries, where appropriate.
    19	- **[Prefetching](/docs/app/getting-started/linking-and-navigating#prefetching):** When a link to a new route enters the user's viewport, Next.js prefetches the route in background. This makes navigation to new routes almost instant. You can opt out of prefetching, where appropriate.
    20	- **[Prerendering](/docs/app/glossary#prerendering):** Next.js prerenders Server and Client Components on the server at build time and caches the rendered result to improve your application's performance. You can opt into [Dynamic Rendering](/docs/app/glossary#dynamic-rendering) for specific routes, where appropriate. {/* TODO: Update when PPR is stable */}
    21	- **[Caching](/docs/app/getting-started/caching):** Next.js caches data requests, the rendered result of Server and Client Components, static assets, and more, to reduce the number of network requests to your server, database, and backend services. You may opt out of caching, where appropriate.
    22	
    23	</AppOnly>
    24	
    25	<PagesOnly>
    26	
    27	- **[Code-splitting](/docs/pages/building-your-application/routing/pages-and-layouts):** Next.js automatically code-splits your application code by pages. This means only the code needed for the current page is loaded on navigation. You may also consider [lazy loading](/docs/pages/guides/lazy-loading) third-party libraries, where appropriate.
    28	- **[Prefetching](/docs/pages/api-reference/components/link#prefetch):** When a link to a new route enters the user's viewport, Next.js prefetches the route in background. This makes navigation to new routes almost instant. You can opt out of prefetching, where appropriate.
    29	- **[Automatic Static Optimization](/docs/pages/building-your-application/rendering/automatic-static-optimization):** Next.js automatically determines that a page is static (can be prerendered) if it has no blocking data requirements. Optimized pages can be cached, and served to the end-user from multiple CDN locations. You may opt into [Server-side Rendering](/docs/pages/building-your-application/data-fetching/get-server-side-props), where appropriate.
    30	
    31	</PagesOnly>
    32	
    33	These defaults aim to improve your application's performance, and reduce the cost and amount of data transferred on each network request.
    34	
    35	## During development
    36	
    37	While building your application, we recommend using the following features to ensure the best performance and user experience:
    38	
    39	### Routing and rendering
    40	
    41	<AppOnly>
    42	
    43	- **[Layouts](/docs/app/api-reference/file-conventions/layout):** Use layouts to share UI across pages and enable [partial rendering](/docs/app/getting-started/linking-and-navigating#client-side-transitions) on navigation.
    44	- **[`<Link>` component](/docs/app/api-reference/components/link):** Use the `<Link>` component for [client-side navigation and prefetching](/docs/app/getting-started/linking-and-navigating#how-navigation-works).
    45	- **[Error Handling](/docs/app/getting-started/error-handling):** Gracefully handle [catch-all errors](/docs/app/getting-started/error-handling) and [404 errors](/docs/app/api-reference/file-conventions/not-found) in production by creating custom error pages.
    46	- **[Client and Server Components](/docs/app/getting-started/server-and-client-components#examples):** Follow the recommended composition patterns for Server and Client Components, and check the placement of your [`"use client"` boundaries](/docs/app/getting-started/server-and-client-components#reducing-js-bundle-size) to avoid unnecessarily increasing your client-side JavaScript bundle.
    47	- **Request-time APIs:** Be aware that Request-time APIs like [`cookies`](/docs/app/api-reference/functions/cookies) and the [`searchParams`](/docs/app/api-reference/file-conventions/page#searchparams-optional) prop will opt the entire route into [Dynamic Rendering](/docs/app/glossary#dynamic-rendering) (or your whole application if used in the [Root Layout](/docs/app/api-reference/file-conventions/layout#root-layout)). Ensure Request-time API usage is intentional and wrap them in `<Suspense>` boundaries where appropriate.
    48	
    49	> **Good to know**: [Partial Prerendering (experimental)](/blog/next-14#partial-prerendering-preview) will allow parts of a route to be dynamic without opting the whole route into dynamic rendering.
    50	
    51	</AppOnly>
    52	
    53	<PagesOnly>
    54	
    55	- **[`<Link>` component](/docs/pages/building-your-application/routing/linking-and-navigating):** Use the `<Link>` component for client-side navigation and prefetching.
    56	- **[Custom Errors](/docs/pages/building-your-application/routing/custom-error):** Gracefully handle [500](/docs/pages/building-your-application/routing/custom-error#500-page) and [404 errors](/docs/pages/building-your-application/routing/custom-error#404-page)
    57	
    58	</PagesOnly>
    59	
    60	### Data fetching and caching
    61	
    62	<AppOnly>
    63	
    64	- **[Server Components](/docs/app/getting-started/fetching-data):** Leverage the benefits of fetching data on the server using Server Components.
    65	- **[Route Handlers](/docs/app/api-reference/file-conventions/route):** Use Route Handlers to access your backend resources from Client Components. But do not call Route Handlers from Server Components to avoid an additional server request.
    66	- **[Streaming](/docs/app/api-reference/file-conventions/loading):** Use Loading UI and React Suspense to progressively send UI from the server to the client, and prevent the whole route from blocking while data is being fetched.
    67	- **[Parallel Data Fetching](/docs/app/getting-started/fetching-data#parallel-data-fetching):** Reduce network waterfalls by fetching data in parallel, where appropriate.
    68	- **[Data Caching](/docs/app/getting-started/caching):** Verify whether your data requests are being cached or not, and opt into caching, where appropriate. Ensure requests that don't use `fetch` are [cached](/docs/app/api-reference/functions/unstable_cache).
    69	- **[Static Images](/docs/app/api-reference/file-conventions/public-folder):** Use the `public` directory to automatically cache your application's static assets, e.g. images.
    70	
    71	</AppOnly>
    72	
    73	<PagesOnly>
    74	
    75	- **[API Routes](/docs/pages/building-your-application/routing/api-routes):** Use Route Handlers to access your backend resources, and prevent sensitive secrets from being exposed to the client.
    76	- **[Data Caching](/docs/pages/building-your-application/data-fetching/get-static-props):** Verify whether your data requests are being cached or not, and opt into caching, where appropriate. Ensure requests that don't use `getStaticProps` are cached where appropriate.
    77	- **[Incremental Static Regeneration](/docs/pages/guides/incremental-static-regeneration):** Use Incremental Static Regeneration to update static pages after they've been built, without rebuilding your entire site.
    78	- **[Static Images](/docs/pages/api-reference/file-conventions/public-folder):** Use the `public` directory to automatically cache your application's static assets, e.g. images.
    79	
    80	</PagesOnly>
    81	
    82	### UI and accessibility
    83	
    84	<AppOnly>
    85	
    86	- **[Forms and Validation](/docs/app/guides/forms):** Use Server Actions to handle form submissions, server-side validation, and handle errors.
    87	- **[Global Error UI](/docs/app/api-reference/file-conventions/error#global-error):** Add `app/global-error.tsx` to provide consistent, accessible fallback UI and recovery for uncaught errors across your app.
    88	- **[Global 404](/docs/app/api-reference/file-conventions/not-found#global-not-foundjs-experimental):** Add `app/global-not-found.tsx` to serve an accessible 404 for unmatched routes across your app.
    89	
    90	</AppOnly>
    91	
    92	- **[Font Module](/docs/app/api-reference/components/font):** Optimize fonts by using the Font Module, which automatically hosts your font files with other static assets, removes external network requests, and reduces [layout shift](https://web.dev/articles/cls).
    93	- **[`<Image>` Component](/docs/app/api-reference/components/image):** Optimize images by using the Image Component, which automatically optimizes images, prevents layout shift, and serves them in modern formats like WebP.
    94	- **[`<Script>` Component](/docs/app/guides/scripts):** Optimize third-party scripts by using the Script Component, which automatically defers scripts and prevents them from blocking the main thread.
    95	- **[ESLint](/docs/architecture/accessibility#linting):** Use the built-in `eslint-plugin-jsx-a11y` plugin to catch accessibility issues early.
    96	
    97	### Security
    98	
    99	<AppOnly>
   100	
   101	- **[Tainting](/docs/app/api-reference/config/next-config-js/taint):** Prevent sensitive data from being exposed to the client by tainting data objects and/or specific values.
   102	- **[Server Actions](/docs/app/getting-started/mutating-data):** Verify authentication and authorization inside each action. Do not rely on Proxy or layout or page level checks alone. Move database access to a `server-only` [Data Access Layer](/docs/app/guides/data-security#data-access-layer) and consider [rate limiting](/docs/app/guides/backend-for-frontend#rate-limiting) for expensive operations. Review the recommended [security practices](/blog/security-nextjs-server-components-actions).
   103	
   104	</AppOnly>
   105	
   106	- **[Environment Variables](/docs/app/guides/environment-variables):** Ensure your `.env.*` files are added to `.gitignore` and only public variables are prefixed with `NEXT_PUBLIC_`.
   107	- **[Content Security Policy](/docs/app/guides/content-security-policy):** Consider adding a Content Security Policy to protect your application against various security threats such as cross-site scripting, clickjacking, and other code injection attacks.
   108	
   109	### Metadata and SEO
   110	
   111	<AppOnly>
   112	
   113	- **[Metadata API](/docs/app/getting-started/metadata-and-og-images):** Use the Metadata API to improve your application's Search Engine Optimization (SEO) by adding page titles, descriptions, and more.
   114	- **[Open Graph (OG) images](/docs/app/api-reference/file-conventions/metadata/opengraph-image):** Create OG images to prepare your application for social sharing.
   115	- **[Sitemaps](/docs/app/api-reference/functions/generate-sitemaps) and [Robots](/docs/app/api-reference/file-conventions/metadata/robots):** Help Search Engines crawl and index your pages by generating sitemaps and robots files.
   116	
   117	</AppOnly>
   118	
   119	<PagesOnly>
   120	
   121	- **[`<Head>` Component](/docs/pages/api-reference/components/head):** Use the `next/head` component to add page titles, descriptions, and more.
   122	
   123	</PagesOnly>
   124	
   125	### Type safety
   126	
   127	- **TypeScript and [TS Plugin](/docs/app/api-reference/config/typescript):** Use TypeScript and the TypeScript plugin for better type-safety, and to help you catch errors early.
   128	
   129	## Before going to production
   130	
   131	Before going to production, you can run `next build` to build your application locally and catch any build errors, then run `next start` to measure the performance of your application in a production-like environment.
   132	
   133	### Core Web Vitals
   134	
   135	- **[Lighthouse](https://developers.google.com/web/tools/lighthouse):** Run lighthouse in incognito to gain a better understanding of how your users will experience your site, and to identify areas for improvement. This is a simulated test and should be paired with looking at field data (such as Core Web Vitals).
   136	
   137	<AppOnly>
   138	
   139	- **[`useReportWebVitals` hook](/docs/app/api-reference/functions/use-report-web-vitals):** Use this hook to send [Core Web Vitals](https://web.dev/articles/vitals) data to analytics tools.
   140	
   141	</AppOnly>
   142	
   143	### Analyzing bundles
   144	
   145	Use the [`@next/bundle-analyzer` plugin](/docs/app/guides/package-bundling#nextbundle-analyzer-for-webpack) to analyze the size of your JavaScript bundles and identify large modules and dependencies that might be impacting your application's performance.
   146	
   147	Additionally, the following tools can help you understand the impact of adding new dependencies to your application:
   148	
   149	- [Import Cost](https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=wix.vscode-import-cost)
   150	- [Package Phobia](https://packagephobia.com/)
   151	- [Bundle Phobia](https://bundlephobia.com/)
   152	- [bundlejs](https://bundlejs.com/)
     1	---
     2	title: How to use environment variables in Next.js
     3	nav_title: Environment Variables
     4	description: Learn to add and access environment variables in your Next.js application.
     5	---
     6	
     7	{/* The content of this doc is shared between the app and pages router. You can use the `<PagesOnly>Content</PagesOnly>` component to add content that is specific to the Pages Router. Any shared content should not be wrapped in a component. */}
     8	
     9	Next.js comes with built-in support for environment variables, which allows you to do the following:
    10	
    11	- [Use `.env` to load environment variables](#loading-environment-variables)
    12	- [Bundle environment variables for the browser by prefixing with `NEXT_PUBLIC_`](#bundling-environment-variables-for-the-browser)
    13	
    14	> **Warning:** The default `create-next-app` template ensures all `.env` files are added to your `.gitignore`. You almost never want to commit these files to your repository.
    15	
    16	## Loading Environment Variables
    17	
    18	Next.js has built-in support for loading environment variables from `.env*` files into `process.env`.
    19	
    20	```txt filename=".env"
    21	DB_HOST=localhost
    22	DB_USER=myuser
    23	DB_PASS=mypassword
    24	```
    25	
    26	<PagesOnly>
    27	
    28	This loads `process.env.DB_HOST`, `process.env.DB_USER`, and `process.env.DB_PASS` into the Node.js environment automatically allowing you to use them in [Next.js data fetching methods](/docs/pages/building-your-application/data-fetching) and [API routes](/docs/pages/building-your-application/routing/api-routes).
    29	
    30	For example, using [`getStaticProps`](/docs/pages/building-your-application/data-fetching/get-static-props):
    31	
    32	```js filename="pages/index.js"
    33	export async function getStaticProps() {
    34	  const db = await myDB.connect({
    35	    host: process.env.DB_HOST,
    36	    username: process.env.DB_USER,
    37	    password: process.env.DB_PASS,
    38	  })
    39	  // ...
    40	}
    41	```
    42	
    43	</PagesOnly>
    44	
    45	<AppOnly>
    46	
    47	> **Note**: Next.js also supports multiline variables inside of your `.env*` files:
    48	>
    49	> ```bash
    50	> # .env
    51	>
    52	> # you can write with line breaks
    53	> PRIVATE_KEY="-----BEGIN RSA PRIVATE KEY-----
    54	> ...
    55	> Kh9NV...
    56	> ...
    57	> -----END DSA PRIVATE KEY-----"
    58	>
    59	> # or with `\n` inside double quotes
    60	> PRIVATE_KEY="-----BEGIN RSA PRIVATE KEY-----\nKh9NV...\n-----END DSA PRIVATE KEY-----\n"
    61	> ```
    62	
    63	> **Note**: If you are using a `/src` folder, please note that Next.js will load the .env files **only** from the parent folder and **not** from the `/src` folder.
    64	> This loads `process.env.DB_HOST`, `process.env.DB_USER`, and `process.env.DB_PASS` into the Node.js environment automatically allowing you to use them in [Route Handlers](/docs/app/api-reference/file-conventions/route).
    65	
    66	For example:
    67	
    68	```js filename="app/api/route.js"
    69	export async function GET() {
    70	  const db = await myDB.connect({
    71	    host: process.env.DB_HOST,
    72	    username: process.env.DB_USER,
    73	    password: process.env.DB_PASS,
    74	  })
    75	  // ...
    76	}
    77	```
    78	
    79	</AppOnly>
    80	
    81	### Loading Environment Variables with `@next/env`
    82	
    83	If you need to load environment variables outside of the Next.js runtime, such as in a root config file for an ORM or test runner, you can use the `@next/env` package.
    84	
    85	This package is used internally by Next.js to load environment variables from `.env*` files.
    86	
    87	To use it, install the package and use the `loadEnvConfig` function to load the environment variables:
    88	
    89	```bash package="pnpm"
    90	pnpm add @next/env
    91	```
    92	
    93	```bash package="npm"
    94	npm install @next/env
    95	```
    96	
    97	```bash package="yarn"
    98	yarn add @next/env
    99	```
   100	
   101	```bash package="bun"
   102	bun add @next/env
   103	```
   104	
   105	```tsx filename="envConfig.ts" switcher
   106	import { loadEnvConfig } from '@next/env'
   107	
   108	const projectDir = process.cwd()
   109	loadEnvConfig(projectDir)
   110	```
   111	
   112	```jsx filename="envConfig.js" switcher
   113	import { loadEnvConfig } from '@next/env'
   114	
   115	const projectDir = process.cwd()
   116	loadEnvConfig(projectDir)
   117	```
   118	
   119	Then, you can import the configuration where needed. For example:
   120	
   121	```tsx filename="orm.config.ts" switcher
   122	import './envConfig.ts'
   123	
   124	export default defineConfig({
   125	  dbCredentials: {
   126	    connectionString: process.env.DATABASE_URL!,
   127	  },
   128	})
   129	```
   130	
   131	```jsx filename="orm.config.js" switcher
   132	import './envConfig.js'
   133	
   134	export default defineConfig({
   135	  dbCredentials: {
   136	    connectionString: process.env.DATABASE_URL,
   137	  },
   138	})
   139	```
   140	
   141	### Referencing Other Variables
   142	
   143	Next.js will automatically expand variables that use `$` to reference other variables e.g. `$VARIABLE` inside of your `.env*` files. This allows you to reference other secrets. For example:
   144	
   145	```txt filename=".env"
   146	TWITTER_USER=nextjs
   147	TWITTER_URL=https://x.com/$TWITTER_USER
   148	```
   149	
   150	In the above example, `process.env.TWITTER_URL` would be set to `https://x.com/nextjs`.
   151	
   152	> **Good to know**: If you need to use variable with a `$` in the actual value, it needs to be escaped e.g. `\$`.
   153	
   154	## Bundling Environment Variables for the Browser
   155	
   156	Non-`NEXT_PUBLIC_` environment variables are only available in the Node.js environment, meaning they aren't accessible to the browser (the client runs in a different _environment_).
   157	
   158	In order to make the value of an environment variable accessible in the browser, Next.js can "inline" a value, at build time, into the js bundle that is delivered to the client, replacing all references to `process.env.[variable]` with a hard-coded value. To tell it to do this, you just have to prefix the variable with `NEXT_PUBLIC_`. For example:
   159	
   160	```txt filename=".env"
   161	NEXT_PUBLIC_ANALYTICS_ID=abcdefghijk
   162	```
   163	
   164	This will tell Next.js to replace all references to `process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_ANALYTICS_ID` in the Node.js environment with the value from the environment in which you run `next build`, allowing you to use it anywhere in your code. It will be inlined into any JavaScript sent to the browser.
   165	
   166	> **Note**: After being built, your app will no longer respond to changes to these environment variables. For instance, if you use a Heroku pipeline to promote slugs built in one environment to another environment, or if you build and deploy a single Docker image to multiple environments, all `NEXT_PUBLIC_` variables will be frozen with the value evaluated at build time, so these values need to be set appropriately when the project is built. If you need access to runtime environment values, you'll have to setup your own API to provide them to the client (either on demand or during initialization).
   167	
   168	```js filename="pages/index.js"
   169	import setupAnalyticsService from '../lib/my-analytics-service'
   170	
   171	// 'NEXT_PUBLIC_ANALYTICS_ID' can be used here as it's prefixed by 'NEXT_PUBLIC_'.
   172	// It will be transformed at build time to `setupAnalyticsService('abcdefghijk')`.
   173	setupAnalyticsService(process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_ANALYTICS_ID)
   174	
   175	function HomePage() {
   176	  return <h1>Hello World</h1>
   177	}
   178	
   179	export default HomePage
   180	```
   181	
   182	Note that dynamic lookups will _not_ be inlined, such as:
   183	
   184	```js
   185	// This will NOT be inlined, because it uses a variable
   186	const varName = 'NEXT_PUBLIC_ANALYTICS_ID'
   187	setupAnalyticsService(process.env[varName])
   188	
   189	// This will NOT be inlined, because it uses a variable
   190	const env = process.env
   191	setupAnalyticsService(env.NEXT_PUBLIC_ANALYTICS_ID)
   192	```
   193	
   194	### Runtime Environment Variables
   195	
   196	Next.js can support both build time and runtime environment variables.
   197	
   198	**By default, environment variables are only available on the server**. To expose an environment variable to the browser, it must be prefixed with `NEXT_PUBLIC_`. However, these public environment variables will be inlined into the JavaScript bundle during `next build`.
   199	
   200	<PagesOnly>
   201	
   202	To read runtime environment variables, we recommend using `getServerSideProps` or [incrementally adopting the App Router](/docs/app/guides/migrating/app-router-migration).
   203	
   204	</PagesOnly>
   205	
   206	<AppOnly>
   207	
   208	You can safely read environment variables on the server during dynamic rendering:
   209	
   210	```tsx filename="app/page.ts" switcher
   211	import { connection } from 'next/server'
   212	
   213	export default async function Component() {
   214	  await connection()
   215	  // cookies, headers, and other Request-time APIs
   216	  // will also opt into dynamic rendering, meaning
   217	  // this env variable is evaluated at runtime
   218	  const value = process.env.MY_VALUE
   219	  // ...
   220	}
